This is a very good idea, and it's still relevant.  We need a way to have our syntax not change, but dispatch to different shell files depending on which shell is in use.  You could lump them all into one file, but that would get hairy.  This PR seems to be missing the env-activate script that it uses to do that dispatch, though.

This kind of thing would be critical to properly supporting fish, dash, ksh, etc.

@pelson how would you like to proceed with this PR?  this is something we need to fix, and if you have a good start on the shell dispatch, I think we'd be happy to take over if you're too busy.

@M0rtenB, I wish it were as obvious to me as it is to you that we can come up with a single metric that allows us to compare significantly disparate package plans. I encourage you to study how conda.resolve does it now and come up with a better plan. There are _myriad_ tradeoffs that one has to consider when updating a bunch of packages at once.

About those channel priority issues. There is indeed a bug there, but it's not quite what you think. The solver _is_ respecting your channel priority setting. However, in that first installation, it has been forced to downgrade some packages in order to upgrade others. And the part of the conda code that tries to _understand_ and _print_ the solution is misinterpreting that. It thinks that it is a channel priority issue, but it's not.

That's definitely a bug. The solution, though, is not a change to the solver, but rather a change to the words conda uses to describe an upgrade/downgrade plan.

@kalefranz, @mingwandroid @msarahan.
Sorry for pinging all of you, but we haven't seen a response on this so far although it is really important for conda-forge and bioconda communities that this solver behavior is fixed, or that you help us to fix it by providing some information on @mbargull's questions. More and more users are hitting these issues, and it seriously hampers their experience with conda. Both communities are seeing a lot of new users these days. It is important to provide a smooth experience and generate trust in conda as a system.

CC @jakirkham

